                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;Missing a crucial point: If the said commit was previously &apos;pushed&apos; to the remote, any &apos;undo&apos; operation, no matter how simple, will cause enormous pain and suffering to the rest of the users who have this commit in their local copy, when they do a &apos;git pull&apos; in the future.  So, if the commit was already &apos;pushed&apos;, do this instead:      git revert &amp;lt;bad-commit-sha1-id&amp;gt;     git push origin :&lt;/span&gt;

